post_text: Meet your new ESUHSD Student Governing Board! Independence High School senior, Bruce Nguyen, was elected as the Chair, Francine Estranero from James Lick as Vice-Chair, Paula Escobar from Evergreen Valley as Secretary, and Angela Huynh from Silver Creek as Public Relations Officer. Board Trustee Lorena Chavez serves as the Governing Board Member Liaison to the Student Governing Board. The members attend monthly virtual meetings to develop and discuss proposals that represent student interests across the district. #ESUHSDProud

post_text:
Friendly Reminder!
-The first day of school is August 11th.
-All instruction will be done through distance learning.
-Please visit our esuhsd.org website for more information.
-If you have any questions please contact your school site, phone numbers can be found on our websites.
-For the first day of school students will receive video conferencing links for each of their classes.
-All ESUHSD students are required to report to their classes on the first day by logging into their video conference link
-Attendance will be taken and monitored.
-If students need a device and connectivity please contact your child's school.

post_text:
The school board unanimously voted last week to put a $60 million general obligation bond on the March 3 ballot to pay for a 100-unit apartment complex for teachers and staff. It will be built on 4.5 acres of district property at 830 N. Capitol Avenue, adjacent to the district‚Äôs main office.

The school board unanimously voted last week to put a $60 million general obligation bond on the March 3 ballot to pay for a 100-unit apartment complex for teachers and staff. It will be built on 4.5 acres of district property at 830 N. Capitol Avenue, adjacent to the district‚Äôs main office.

post_text: Yerba Buena High School's all-girls MESA team won 1st place at the Cisco Girls Power Tech Innovation Challenge, beating college and high school competitors! The team built a fully functioning AI-inspired prototype to alleviate the trash problem associated with homelessness in our community. Their product, named H2GO, was designed to incentivize people for bringing in garbage by dispensing a water bottle for every bag deposited. The machine was designed to sort the trash and categorize as landfill, organic, or recyclable. #ESUHSDProud

post_text:
James Lick and Andrew Hill high school students have been working hard on their science, engineering, and tech projects, such as building a fully rotational prosthetic arm & hand with an extendable reach, building and coding robots, among many other unique projects that will be competing in this year's ESUHSD #sciencepalooza! event.

Students are part of the Future Advancers of Science and Technology (FAST) program, in which Stanford University Ph.D. students meet twice a month with our high school students to brainstorm science and technology projects, carry out experiments, and build prototypes. #ESUHSDProud

post_text: Mt. Pleasant High School is proud to announce the opening of a new crosswalk as part of our commitment to public safety!
shared_text:
Magdalena Carrasco is with Peter Ortiz and 11 others.
January 11, 2019 at 8:52 PM ¬∑

We had such a great turnout this morning as we cut the ribbon to commemorate a crosswalk two years in the making in the Mt. Pleasant neighborhood. Thank you to everyone who worked so hard to elevate people's concerns and collaborate with my office to identify safety concerns. Please thank Melissa Got-Lopez from the Mt. Pleasant Neighborhood Association, Mt. Pleasant High School Principal Martha Guerrero, and Cordell Bailey from our Department of Transportation. I am happy to say that our children and families can cross this busy street with more confidence, pride, and protection. Please continue to engage with my office and me about areas in District 5 that could be made safer!

Thank you to everyone who worked so hard to elevate people's concerns and collaborate with my office to identify safety concerns. Please thank Melissa Got-Lopez from the Mt. Pleasant Neighborhood Association, Mt. Pleasant High School Principal Martha Guerrero, and Cordell Bailey from our Department of Transportation. post_text:
After winning 1st, 2nd, and 3rd place in the National Engineering Design Competition on a regional level, Santa Teresa High School's Mathematics Engineering Science Achievement (MESA) team advanced to the State Competition and placed 2nd.

The mighty team of 4 (Bruce, Christopher, Ganesh, and Marek) focused on their "BreeziHome" concept, a system that would automatically open and close windows to efficiently regulate a home's inside temperature.

post_text:
Martha Cabrera, a community involvement specialist at Oak Grove High School, has been nominated for the "LifeChanger of the Year Award" for her endless support of students and their families and for creating multiple opportunities for students to succeed.

This year, she ran a food pantry at school that serves about 300 families every month, giving out thousands of pounds of food to families in need. The food pantry is in partnership with Second Harvest Food Bank, http://blog.shfb.org/index.php/2018/05/03/schools-reach-hungry-kids/

post_text:
Congratulations to Jalen from Oak Grove High School, first place winner at NFTE's Regional Youth Entrepreneurship Challenge! He received $1,500 in seed capital for his "Power Bikes" entrepreneurial concept, a solar/kinetic power station for bicycles.

Jalen will be heading to New York City in October to compete for a $15,000 grand prize at NFTE's National Challenge.
